    <h2>FAQ</h2>
    <h3>What number bases are supported?</h3>
    <p>Binary (base 2), Octal (base 8), Decimal (base 10), and Hexadecimal (base 16).</p>

    <h3>Is there a size limit?</h3>
    <p>The tool uses BigInt for arbitrary precision, so it can handle very large numbers. Input is limited to 1MB.</p>

    <h3>Is my data safe?</h3>
    <p>Yes. All conversion happens in your browser. No data is sent to any server.</p>

    <h3>How do I convert a hex color to RGB?</h3>
    <p>Split the hex code into three pairs and convert each from hex to decimal. For example, <code>#1A2B3C</code> → R: <code>1A</code> = 26, G: <code>2B</code> = 43, B: <code>3C</code> = 60. Paste each pair into this tool with HEX selected to get the decimal value instantly.</p>

    <h3>Why does programming use hexadecimal so often?</h3>
    <p>One hex digit represents exactly 4 binary bits (a nibble), so two hex digits represent one byte (8 bits). This makes hex a compact and readable shorthand for binary data — far easier to scan than a long string of 0s and 1s.</p>
  </Fragment>
